THERE ARE JUST! A lot of interesting questions and dynamics in this series. Like at it's base "vampires as the embodiment of colonization so we can punch them in the fucking face" but as any good horror goes...there's so much more than that one satisfaction

And Neeks (Tyson's bloodhunter-to-be daughter) makes as many the decisions as Tyson; in part bc i think Tyson believes in her leadership and wants to support her on her path, even if it frightens him...and bc Neeks as the child of an alcoholic knows he's not always going reliable

In Firebite the main physical character is an alcoholic. His daughter/protege is tough as nails but often singleminded-to-a-fault (there's a Bruce Lee poster that comes up and I can't help but think of characters like her in martial arts/wuxia series)

something to be said about aligning femininity to nature and "the savage" for sure, and yes i like to see physically strong women kick ass too, but we have enough (white) action films and physical strength shouldn't be a prerequisite to putting a character into a story

and one of the interesting notes was that even the most "feeble" and "hysterical" woman in a ghost story are by nature of the genre given the power and agency to fight back bc characters are given the opportunity to effect the outcome outside of the limitations of the body
I was listening to an episode of the evolution of horror podcast about ghost stories and how some of the first notable (western) ghost films starred women

maybe that sounds ironic from someone who watches a lot of horror but the violence has to serve a purpose beyond filling the stereotype of a victim narrative that shoulders the entire history of genocide into one character or gender

one of the things i find really difficult in watching Indig media, even when it is Indigenous led, is of course the victimization of Indigenous women; like yes that is a story but it is NOT the only story
One of the things I appreciate the most about Firebite is everyone is given the opportunity to fight back and everyone snaps to bc they know they gotta

I was so stunned to see my family in this film, and shocked, and profoundly sad for the circumstance, but I was so grateful to see that the crew had operated with care and given me, someone they never could have planned for, the space to more safely view this piece of our history

you know, I am not the best at answering emails promptly, but I just got one back from someone from an inquiry I sent in March 2019 so you know. I'm doing okay.

Today I remembered faith in the work and the importance of looking up from our own battles to show up for our kin. My prayers were heard by yours, on this stolen, unceded land of the Musqueam, Squamish and Tsleil-Waututh #SaveSheikhJarrah #FreePalestine

Our protests, refusals have never gone unheeded by the land; only by the colonial state. My prayers speak to yours and yours to mine; seeking ways to nudge us towards one another with all the knowledge and wisdom that's been accumulated through time. Land has a long memory.

You are always already "on the land", even in what appears to be the most urban, colonized of spaces. The land is beneath, listening, archiving, learning; I think the land holds the prayers, helps them find their way to the right hearts.

I don't think that anyone who comes to the land for refuge, with righteous rage and love in their heart comes to the land without offerings. Today I was reminded of some of my first lessons from Palestinian activists and the land that held the ground for that teaching. Mussi cho.
I am an uninvited, Indigenous guest on MST, but circling back to that question of what it might mean to pray on unceded territories while your own is under siege;

I don't know if this is a problem in my heart, but when I go to protests for our missing and murdered and for our land i am mired in uncertainty. Uncertain if it makes a difference, if there will be change or even if I'll make it home.

The rally was also bigger than any Free Palestine protest I'd ever been to before, despite the pandemic. The chants, and energy was all clear and echoed off the buildings in such a tremendous way. The crowd teemed with families and outrage but above everything, certainty.

contextualizing the colonization of Palestine using the example of unceded MST territories; ten years ago, the first time I attended a rally for Palestine this parallel example wasn't non-existent in conversation, but to hear it ring with such a sincere understanding felt new

My hearing isn't super when there's a lot of noise/stimulus to filter through but one of the speakers today at the rally for Palestine I did manage to catch quite well asked, "what does it mean for me to pray on stolen land?"

if I'm approached for work I expect a certain degree of  someone, Indig or non-Indig, demonstrating that they can see what I'm doing beyond just an aesthetic. It's not ego, it's a way of guarding myself from exploitation.

and more often than not, those chunks of ourselves that we're scraping from the fucking bottom of a barrel in the hopes that we can make something meaningful to show others in our community ends up in modern day curios cabinets.

what i make doesn't fall in the purview of "traditional" or "sacred" but racialized artists, especially those who make identity-based art, aren't afforded the same creative freedoms as white artists to have a degree of separation between ourselves and our work. we ARE our work.

our entire history of art post-contact has been of being robbed, destroyed, diminished, appropriated and mutated by non-Indigenous makers, hoarded in museums, mining artists financially, emotionally and spiritually to fill space in white cubes

like sure, your platform is big but by just dropping in and asking for shit without demonstrating that you have any intention of respecting or defending that work once it's on your platform is not a safe situation for Indigenous artists

on one hand, it's in my nature to give the benefit of the doubt because i hate conflict but on the other I'm like? so tired? of miscellany rando messages from people just trying to round out their content. and they contacted my place of WORK first not just for me but for a LIST.

RT @RussDiabo: Mi'kmaw journalist assesses media coverage of fisheries dispute | CBC News https://t.co/yCofAjGqTz

To sign this agreement without resolving these issues is an unconscionable mismanagement and a breach of trust. I live in a urban centre, but my family is taken care of by that land and we deserve to know what the hell is happening. This agreement is nothing to celebrate.

Lake Babine Nation is an amalgamation of several communities; Fort Babine, or Wit'at, has had rumblings of separating for ever; much of this forestry is happening directly on our clans territories but the resources get funnelled disproportionately to Burns Lake.

Prior to this gas station/grocery store combo, the last official business in Fort Babine was the Hudson Bay in the 70s. Until recently, it's been an 1.5hr drive into Smithers for essentials. We have elders and young families living up there with no vehicles or unreliable ones.

My nation has one of the largest forestry businesses in our territory but trouble has been brewing for years; if you go to Fort Babine, where are those resources going? We have no housing, no medical, the biggest news in recent years is finally having a store on reserve again.

"Alec says the agreement also outlines how the three levels of government will work together to enact the First Nation's rights and title over its territory in central B.C."

I don't think we need any colonial level of government telling us how to enact rights and title

Indig communities pour so much love (and money) into this sport. But when it comes to Chicago, and even the ndns who love that team, you don't get to see how much that all means. You just see the logo; that's the message of "Indigenous" that gets broadcast worldwide.

so i often feel dumb worrying about a logo. but when it's all this big, when you see the tremendous place this sport has in our communities and the true and genuine joy it can bring --seeing that Chicago logo bites. Hard.

and walking around cemeteries in rural communities (what, it's quiet) you can see the amazing fucking SHRINES of NHL memorabilia decking out ppls headstones. and it's not exclusive to Indig folks of course, but it's a lot.

my community is pretty poor and i used to balk at folks wearing their hockey jerseys to funerals. but it was explained to me that ppl would wear the jersey for the deceased's favourite team and i was like oh SHIT, right. You maybe have a suit for like...if you're on band council.
to be able to do all that is already a step towards even the POSSIBILITY of not just greater things, but like, legendary shit. to be able to dream that big is a rare privilege.

native kids grow up dreaming of being in the NHL; but even making it onto a team, making to practice, affording the gear, dealing with racist bs, then if you're a girl and you stick with the game when the reality that NHL isn't going to be co-ed any time soon...

i have trouble coming into my community but hockey is SUCH an entry point back in. If my urban ndn, trans, gay ass can come in and say something informed about this shit, that wins respect and bonus points for my (now legitimate) enthusiasm.

am I asking for a public Ian Campeau style apology from Jarrett Martineau? No, bc fuck 'em both. Apologies like that only help them. But I at least want anyone who's read this far to know that you gotta watch out for Jarrett bc institutions still hand him power.

I don't want to have to spend my whole career in a whisper network, hoping no one falls out of that safety net or into situations where colonial institutions have the power to constantly assist these men in repositioning themselves.

where Indigenous trans women don't have to second guess every step in a career they should have the room to cherish as exciting and fulfilling, where queer Indig folks don't have their knowledge foisted up and claimed by Indig men who haven't done the work.

It's not a victim's responsibility to take these men up onto stage. I've always been fortunate enough to have art aunties watching out for me and telling me who to avoid. but i also dream of a creative world where these warnings aren't needed.

which takes me to the next distressing thing: Jarrett had so easily transplanted himself into the west coast into another institution that doesn't know the whisper network shit and was again being held up as someone to rely on for young (and in my case queer) Indig ppl
but that's the fucked thing, right? there are so many ntv men in our arts communities that we just have to stay away from for either our professional or physical safety.

I won't mention specific ppl bc those aren't my stories and my point is that he garnered enough even be on the whisper shit list. I can only speak towards Jarrett in the sense of I've been told to stay away from him.

my hair is always a point of contention for me bc culturally, not a super gendered thing for me, but outside of cultures where long hair for men is normalized, becomes this signaling flag that feels so dangerous in certain situations
it's wild to me that I've come to bank so much of my safety on the fucking cut of a pair of jeans but i think esp with my long hair, i feel hyper aware of other parts of my body

i've had top surgery and while my nips are way less cute the flatness of my chest feels so much better and more "correct" and all these things actually do make me feel...tentatively celebratory.

but the fear isn't gone.
sometimes I think T is basically doing fuck all but lately I have noticed more when i see full-body pictures of myself that yeah, my thighs and hips do look a lot different from how they used to

eg. i've had more $$$ the last couple of years to explore different cuts of clothing that don't have to be in the category of largest most amorphous shapes possible, which, is to say that being able to do that had been such a privilege

clothing becomes armour, and as much as I don't like to hyperfocus specific features, it is linked to safety and lately i've been feeling better about it bc of certain privileges that have come up in addition to thin privilege.

it's this weird thing where I wouldn't say it's led to any eating disorders specifically for fear of exaggerating those features, but I certainly have a lot of disordered eating habits as a result of the larger, nebulous cloud of mental health bs and it sometimes comes into play

i'm very self-conscious about the shape of my hips & thighs re: passing (complicated bc it's not even an aspiration of mine to pass as a cis man) but I've always felt that they put my body in that dangerous ambigous space of questioning.

thinking about Pride and queer culture and my conflict between the pressure to celebrate one's body, of actually enjoying one's body and then also the reality of having to factor in safety as BIPOC trans folk for many meat spaces in the world
